TERRAFORM STATE 
----------------
terraform stores state in the current working directory in a JSON formatted file named terraform.tfstate.
terraform needs to lock the state file while performing any action that might write to the file.
terraform can be configured to store state in shared location. A backend config will determine where state is stored.

Remote state configuration  : Backend configuration goes inside Terraform block, not a provider block.
--------------------------    you must run "terraform init" after adding or changing backend configuration.

S3 As Backend :
-------------
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket = "prod-terraform-state"
    key = "prod/terraform.tfstate"
    region = "us-east-1"  
    use_lockfile = "true"     //enable state locking
  }
}
-------------
terraform {
  backend "azurerm" {
    tenant_id = ""
    client_id = ""
    storage_account_name = ""
    container_name = ""
    key = ""                                 //state locking is automatic in azure and gcp not in aws
  }
}

STATE STORAGE BEST PRACTICES
-----------------------------

Q  : How to migrate state from local to remote state ?
Ans: terraform init -migrate-state

Why inspect terraform state ?
to see what resources terraform is managing.
check the current recorded state of a resource.
troubleshoot why a plan shows unexpected changes.
verify what terraform "thinks" exist.

Inspecting state using the terraform CLI :
------------------------------------------
terraform state list     //list all resources in terraform state
terraform state show  <resource>        //display state or plan details
terraform state mv    -> now moved block   //move a resource 
terraform state rm    -> now remove block   // remove a resource from state
terraform state pull     // download state from current location
terraform state push     //push state to the configured backend











